  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 12:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The inference from the passage cited is obvious, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "εἰς παιδείαν ὑπομένετε",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “it is for training ye are enduring (are called to endure), as sons God is dealing with you”. [",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "προσφέρεται",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is common; as in Xenophon, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "οὐ γὰρ ὡς φίλοι προσεφέροντο ἡμῖν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and in Josephus, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὡς πολεμίοις προσεφέροντο",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".] Their sufferings are evidence that God considers them His sons and treats them as such; for what son is there whom his father does not correct? ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τίς γὰρ υἱὸς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
